   "topic": "Consent in children: parental consent, the mature minor (Gillick), the best-interest / court override, and special procedures (Marion's case)",
   "subarea": "Theatre safety & consent",
   "trap": "Layered rules. (1) Under-18 default: parent/guardian consents in the child's best interests. (2) MATURE MINOR (Gillick competence, approved by the HCA in Marion's case): a child with sufficient understanding/intelligence to fully comprehend the proposed treatment CAN consent themselves — parental consent then not required; competence is assessed per-decision and rises with the gravity of the procedure. (3) OVERRIDE: a court (parens patriae / Family Court) can override BOTH a parent's refusal AND even a competent minor's REFUSAL of life-saving treatment (the classic exam scenario: Jehovah's Witness teen refusing transfusion for leukaemia/haemorrhage) where refusal poses a serious threat to life/health. (4) SPECIAL MEDICAL PROCEDURES require COURT/tribunal authorisation — neither parents nor a Gillick-competent child can authorise non-therapeutic sterilisation (Marion's case), and similar for some irreversible/non-therapeutic procedures. Exam-catch asymmetry: a mature minor's CONSENT can stand alone, but their REFUSAL of life-saving treatment is more readily overridden.",
   "whatFirst": "Assess Gillick competence for THIS decision → competent minor may consent. If refusal of life-saving treatment (minor or parent) → escalate urgently to senior + hospital legal/court (parens patriae). If sterilisation/non-therapeutic special procedure → Family Court/tribunal authorisation regardless of who consents.",
   "discriminator": "Gillick CONSENT vs Gillick REFUSAL: consent by a competent minor is generally sufficient; refusal of life-saving treatment is the situation courts override. Distinguish ordinary surgery (parent or mature minor consents) from SPECIAL procedures (court only — Marion's case).",
   "redFlags": "Parental refusal of clearly life-saving treatment for a child (e.g. transfusion, cancer therapy) = urgent escalation to court — do NOT simply accept it. Proposed sterilisation / non-therapeutic irreversible procedure on a minor = court authorisation mandatory.",
   "mcqTrap": "Tempting WRONG answer: 'Parents of an intellectually disabled 14-year-old can consent to non-therapeutic sterilisation.' WRONG — Marion's case: requires court authorisation. Also wrong: 'a Gillick-competent 15-year-old's refusal of a life-saving transfusion must be respected like an adult's' — a court can override a minor's refusal.",
   "viva": "Examiner probe (ethics native): 'A 15-year-old refuses a life-saving transfusion' — assess Gillick competence, note that a minor's refusal of life-saving Rx can be court-overridden in their best interests, escalate to senior/legal/court. Curveball: 'Could the parents authorise sterilisation?' — No, Marion's case → court.",
   "source": "Secretary, Dept of Health & Community Services v JWB & SMB (Marion's case) [1992] HCA 15; (1992) 175 CLR 218; Gillick competence (adopted in Marion's case); NSW Health Consent Manual (Minors); MDA National / Avant mature-minor guidance.",
