   "topic": "Phases of healing & timing — the 'wound is weakest' MCQ trap (why dehiscence peaks day 5-8)",
   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Phases: Haemostasis (immediate) -> Inflammation (day 0-~3, neutrophils then macrophages) -> Proliferation (day ~3-21: fibroblasts, type III collagen, granulation, angiogenesis, epithelialisation) -> Remodelling/maturation (week 3 to ~1 year: type III collagen replaced by type I, scar matures). Key gotcha: tensile strength is LOWEST around day 5-7 (early proliferative phase — old collagen lysed, new collagen not yet cross-linked) — exactly when abdominal dehiscence peaks. Wound regains only ~20% strength at 3 weeks and a MAXIMUM of ~70-80% of original strength ever (never 100%).",
