   "topic": "Primary vs secondary vs tertiary (delayed primary) wound closure — which heals when, and the MCQ trap",
   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Primary intention = edges apposed immediately (sutures/staples/glue) within hours, minimal granulation, fast, fine scar — used for CLEAN incised wounds. Secondary intention = wound left OPEN to heal by granulation + contraction + re-epithelialisation from the base up (slow, large scar, more contracture) — used for contaminated/infected wounds, large tissue-loss wounds, abscess cavities. Tertiary intention = DELAYED primary closure: deliberately left open ~3-5 days (to control contamination/oedema/infection), then sutured closed once clean. The tempting wrong answer is calling a wound left open then closed later 'secondary intention' — that is tertiary. Secondary intention is NEVER surgically closed; it is left to granulate completely.",
   "whatFirst": "Decide closure method by contamination: clean/clean-contaminated -> primary; grossly contaminated, infected, or significant tissue loss -> secondary; contaminated wound you intend to close after a delay -> tertiary (delayed primary, day 3-5).",
   "discriminator": "Open-then-sutured = tertiary, NOT secondary. Secondary = open until fully granulated, never re-sutured.",
   "redFlags": "A 'clean' wound being left to heal by secondary intention should prompt you to ask why (suspected contamination/ischaemia).",
   "mcqTrap": "Distractor: 'A traumatic wound debrided, left open for 4 days, then sutured heals by secondary intention' — WRONG, that is tertiary/delayed primary intention.",
