   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Dehiscence = separation of a surgical wound along its layers; may be superficial (skin) or full-thickness FASCIAL (burst abdomen). Evisceration = full-thickness dehiscence WITH protrusion of abdominal viscera through the wound — a surgical emergency. Classic timing: abdominal fascial dehiscence peaks DAY 5-8 post-op (lowest tensile strength). The cardinal warning sign is a sudden gush of serosanguineous / 'salmon-pink' / 'pink watery' fluid from the wound — this precedes/heralds dehiscence. Trap: students focus on antibiotics or reassurance when the answer is theatre. Risk = the RACS 'failure' factors (raised intra-abdominal pressure: cough/ileus/obstruction; poor tissue: malnutrition, steroids, diabetes, jaundice, malignancy; technical: closure tension/suture failure; infection).",
