   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "In a post-bowel-resection patient who is 'not quite right' around POD5-7, the FIRST move is to recognise the subtle physiology: persistent/new tachycardia and falling urine output BEFORE frank peritonitis. Take bloods (FBC, CRP, lactate, U&E), examine the abdomen, and escalate to the surgical team — do NOT wait for overt peritonism.",
   "trap": "Classic timing POD5-7 (range 3-10). The earliest and most reliable signs are UNEXPLAINED PERSISTENT TACHYCARDIA (HR that won't settle) and OLIGURIA — these precede fever, pain and peritonitis. A CRP that fails to fall after POD3-4 is a key clue: a CRP RISE >50 mg/L over 24h from POD3 is >96% specific for leak. 'Failure to rally' / prolonged ileus + low-grade confusion in an elderly patient can be the only sign.",
   "discriminator": "Persistent tachycardia + oliguria + CRP not falling POD5-7 after colorectal/upper GI anastomosis = LEAK until proven otherwise — distinguish from a simple wound infection (localised, well systemically) and from atrial fibrillation (do an ECG, but new AF is often itself a leak/sepsis marker). CT abdomen/pelvis with contrast (+/- water-soluble contrast study) is the confirmatory test; a normal early CT does NOT exclude it.",
   "redFlags": "Tachycardia that persists despite fluids, oliguria, rising lactate, peritonism, new AF, or septic shock. ESCALATE: this is a re-laparotomy / source-control situation. Do not discharge a patient with unexplained tachycardia.",
   "mcqTrap": "The seductive wrong answer is to attribute the POD6 tachycardia to 'pain', 'atelectasis' or 'dehydration' and prescribe analgesia/fluids and observe. Persistent tachycardia after bowel surgery = leak; the correct step is urgent senior review + contrast CT, not reassurance.",
   "mnemonic": "'Tachy that won't track down on day 6 = the join's let go.' Leak triad: Tachycardia, low Urine, rising CRP.",
   "viva": "Examiner probes the discriminator: 'Why won't you just give this POD6 patient with HR 110 some morphine and IV fluids?' — articulate that unexplained persistent tachycardia is the earliest sign of anastomotic leak, then ISBAR escalation to the registrar and the need for contrast CT and source control. Consent angle: re-laparotomy / possible stoma.",
   "visualHtml": "<div class=\"gv-flow\"><div class=\"gv-step\">POD5-7 post-bowel resection, patient 'off'</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Check: persistent tachycardia, urine output, CRP trend, lactate</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Tachycardia + oliguria + CRP not falling = suspect LEAK</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Senior review + CT abdo/pelvis with contrast</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Resuscitate + antibiotics + source control (drain / re-laparotomy +/- stoma)</div></div>",
   "source": "POD5-7 timing and tachycardia/oliguria/failure-to-rally presentation per colorectal surgical literature (Dove OAS; ITACS leak study). CRP rise >50 mg/L/24h from POD3 = >96% specific per PMC6997159. Australian antimicrobial framing per Therapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotic (eTG, current).",
