   "topic": "Ileus vs mechanical bowel obstruction — the post-op 'still not opening bowels' call",
   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "Distinguish physiological from pathological FIRST by the clock and the bowel sounds: normal post-op ileus resolves by ~POD3 (small bowel <24h, stomach 24-48h, colon 48-72h). 'Prolonged/paralytic ileus' = failure of bowel function to return by POD3-5 with NO mechanical cause. Examine for distension, listen (absent/quiet sounds = ileus; high-pitched tinkling = obstruction), keep NBM, NG tube if vomiting/distended, correct electrolytes, stop opioids/anticholinergics, and image with CT if not resolving.",
   "trap": "TIMING: investigate persistent ileus beyond POD3-5. KEY DISCRIMINATOR on CT: mechanical obstruction shows a TRANSITION POINT (dilated proximal, collapsed distal bowel); ileus shows DIFFUSE/UNIFORM dilatation with air-fluid levels and NO transition point. CT distinguishes the two with very high accuracy for complete mechanical SBO. Bowel sounds: absent/silent = ileus; high-pitched/tinkling + colicky pain + early vomiting = mechanical obstruction.",
   "discriminator": "Ileus = silent abdomen, generalised gradual distension, less colicky pain, reversible precipitants (opioids, hypokalaemia/hypomagnesaemia, hypothyroid, immobility). Mechanical (often adhesional early post-op) = colicky pain, tinkling sounds, vomiting, transition point on CT. The dangerous overlap is CLOSED-LOOP / strangulating obstruction — constant (not colicky) pain, tachycardia, raised lactate, peritonism = surgical emergency.",
   "redFlags": "Constant severe pain, tachycardia, fever, rising lactate, peritonism, or CT signs of ischaemia/closed loop = strangulation -> theatre. Faeculent vomiting. Massively distended caecum (>9-12 cm) risks perforation.",
   "mcqTrap": "The tempting wrong answer is to take an early post-op 'obstruction' straight to theatre. Most EARLY post-op small-bowel obstruction is adhesional/inflammatory and settles with conservative management (NBM, NG decompression, IV fluids, correct electrolytes) UNLESS there are strangulation red flags. Conversely, mislabelling a true mechanical obstruction as 'ileus' and just waiting is the opposite trap — CT transition point settles it.",
   "mnemonic": "'Silent & even = ileus; tinkling with a transition = obstruction.' Fix the 4 reversibles for ileus: Opioids, Potassium/Magnesium, Mobility, Sepsis.",
   "viva": "Examiner: 'POD4, distended, vomiting, not passing flatus — ileus or obstruction, and how do you tell?' — give the bowel-sound contrast, the reversible precipitants of ileus, and CT transition point as the discriminator; state conservative-first for early adhesional SBO and the strangulation red flags that mandate theatre. ISBAR + consent for laparotomy if strangulating.",
   "visualHtml": "<table class=\"gv-table\"><thead><tr><th></th><th>Paralytic ileus</th><th>Mechanical obstruction</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Pain</td><td>Mild, generalised</td><td>Colicky (constant = strangulation)</td></tr><tr><td>Bowel sounds</td><td>Absent / quiet</td><td>High-pitched, tinkling</td></tr><tr><td>CT</td><td>Diffuse dilatation, no transition</td><td>TRANSITION POINT, distal collapse</td></tr><tr><td>Cause</td><td>Opioids, low K+/Mg2+, immobility, sepsis</td><td>Adhesions, hernia, mass</td></tr><tr><td>First Rx</td><td>NBM, NG, correct electrolytes, stop opioids</td><td>Conservative if early/adhesional; theatre if strangulating</td></tr></tbody></table>",
