   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "ABCDE + SpO2 on room air, RR, HR, temp, and a focused chest exam FIRST. Sit the patient up, give controlled oxygen if hypoxic, get an ECG and CXR, and ABG/VBG if significant hypoxia. The POD and the vitals pattern then steer you to the diagnosis.",
   "trap": "TIMING SPLIT: Atelectasis = POD1-2 (most common early cause, basal crackles, mild desaturation, responds to mobilisation/spirometry). Pneumonia = POD3-5 (productive cough, focal signs, consolidation on CXR, raised WCC/CRP). PE = POD5+ and can be ANY day (sudden pleuritic pain, tachycardia, hypoxia with a CLEAR chest and often a NORMAL/near-normal CXR). The 'clear chest + hypoxia + tachycardia' combination is the PE giveaway.",
   "discriminator": "PE vs atelectasis/pneumonia: PE has hypoxia OUT OF PROPORTION to chest findings and an unremarkable CXR; atelectasis/pneumonia have abnormal CXR. Use the two-tier Wells score: 'PE unlikely' (<=4) -> D-dimer (but D-dimer is unhelpfully raised post-op, so only a low-probability + negative D-dimer is reassuring); 'PE likely' (>4) -> straight to CTPA. CTPA sensitivity ~96-100%, specificity ~89-98%.",
   "redFlags": "Sudden collapse, hypotension, syncope, RV strain on ECG (S1Q3T3, new RBBB), or sustained SpO2 fall = massive PE -> consider thrombolysis. Rising O2 requirement despite physio. Confusion/exhaustion = impending respiratory failure.",
   "mcqTrap": "The trap: POD5 sudden breathlessness with a NORMAL CXR — the tempting wrong answer is 'reassure, this is atelectasis' or 'repeat CXR'. A clear CXR with hypoxia and tachycardia after surgery points to PE -> CTPA, not reassurance. Conversely, treating an obvious POD1 atelectasis with antibiotics is the over-treatment trap.",
