   "topic": "Post-op fever by day — the 5 Ws timeline (when the day points the finger)",
   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "Don't reflexively septic-screen every post-op fever: the POD (post-op day) narrows the cause before you investigate. Examine the wound + legs + IV/cannula sites, check the catheter, look at the chest. A self-limiting fever in the first 24-48h after a big op is usually the inflammatory stress response, NOT infection.",
   "trap": "EXACT TIMELINE: Wind (pneumonia/aspiration/PE; atelectasis often blamed but is NOT a true independent fever cause) POD 1-2 (earliest); Water (UTI, often catheter-associated) POD 3-5; Wound (surgical site infection) POD 5-7; Walking (DVT/PE) POD 5+ and persists for weeks; Wonder drugs / Weird (drug fever, transfusion reaction, line/abscess, anastomotic leak) any time, but think POD 5-7+. IMMEDIATE fever (<6h) with an erythematous/painful/crepitant wound = necrotising soft-tissue infection or Group A strep/clostridial — surgical emergency, NOT routine SSI.",
   "discriminator": "POD1 low-grade fever + clear chest + clear urine after major abdo/thoracic = post-op inflammatory response/early atelectasis (mobilise/incentive spirometry, NOT antibiotics — the most over-treated 'cause'; atelectasis itself is not proven to cause fever). Fever FIRST appearing POD5-7 with rising tachycardia and abdominal signs after bowel surgery = think anastomotic leak, not 'just a wound infection'.",
   "redFlags": "Fever <6h post-op with disproportionate wound pain, crepitus, or grey/dishwater discharge = necrotising soft-tissue infection -> theatre. Fever + hypotension + new confusion = sepsis, escalate. Fever + breathlessness + pleuritic pain POD5+ = PE.",
   "mcqTrap": "The tempting wrong answer is 'start empirical broad-spectrum antibiotics' for an isolated POD1 low-grade fever with a clear septic screen — this is the inflammatory response/atelectasis; the answer is chest physio/mobilisation. Antibiotics here are the distractor.",
   "mnemonic": "5 Ws in day order: Wind (1-2) -> Water (3-5) -> Wound (5-7) -> Walking/veins (5+) -> Wonder drugs/Weird (anytime). 'Wind blows first, the Wound shows late.'",
   "viva": "Examiner probes: 'POD2 spike to 38.2, what first?' — targeted exam (chest, wound, legs, lines, catheter) + the day-based differential, NOT a blind pan-culture. Then ISBAR if unwell. Be ready to justify why you would NOT give antibiotics for an isolated early low-grade fever.",
   "visualHtml": "<table class=\"gv-table\"><thead><tr><th>POD</th><th>W</th><th>Cause</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1-2</td><td>Wind</td><td>Pneumonia/aspiration (atelectasis blamed)</td><td>Mobilise, spirometry, CXR if persists</td></tr><tr><td>3-5</td><td>Water</td><td>UTI (catheter)</td><td>Urinalysis/culture, remove IDC if able</td></tr><tr><td>5-7</td><td>Wound</td><td>SSI +/- deep collection</td><td>Inspect, swab, consider CT for abscess/leak</td></tr><tr><td>5+</td><td>Walking</td><td>DVT / PE</td><td>Doppler / CTPA, Wells</td></tr><tr><td>Any</td><td>Wonder drugs</td><td>Drug fever, transfusion, line sepsis</td><td>Review meds/lines, cultures</td></tr></tbody></table>",
