   "topic": "Australian Sentinel Events List (v2) — the 10 wholly-preventable, externally-reportable events",
   "subarea": "Open disclosure & M&M",
   "trap": "Sentinel events are a defined national subset of adverse events that are wholly preventable and cause serious harm/death — they are ALWAYS SAC 1, mandatorily reported, and trigger RCA + formal open disclosure. The current list (version 2) was agreed by Health Ministers in December 2018 and commenced 1 July 2019, with 10 categories (specifications updated May 2025). The classic surgical gotchas (the ‘wrong-wrong-wrong + retained + ABO’ cluster) all sit here. MCQs love asking which scenario IS a listed sentinel event vs merely a serious complication — e.g. a recognised, consented complication of surgery is NOT a sentinel event; wrong-site surgery IS.",
   "source": "Australian Sentinel Events List version 2 Specifications, ACSQHC (commenced 1 July 2019; specifications updated May 2025)",
   "discriminator": "Sentinel event = on the defined list, wholly preventable, never-event style. A serious but recognised/consented complication (e.g. anastomotic leak, expected bleeding) is an adverse event but NOT a sentinel event. Wrong patient/site/procedure, retained object, ABO-incompatible transfusion = sentinel. Use the WHO checklist / surgical time-out as the prevention link for the surgical four.",
   "whatFirst": "Identify it as a sentinel event → ensure patient safety → mandatory external notification per jurisdiction → secure evidence (e.g. retained item, blood bag) → commence formal open disclosure → RCA. Do not delay patient disclosure pending the RCA.",
   "redFlags": "Any of: wrong site, wrong patient, wrong procedure, retained foreign object, ABO-incompatible haemolytic transfusion, in-patient suicide (acute psychiatric), serious medication error, restraint-related serious harm, infant/child discharge to unauthorised person, mis-placed naso/oro-gastric tube causing serious harm → mandatory reporting + RCA.",
   "mcqTrap": "‘A patient develops an anastomotic leak after consented bowel resection — this is a sentinel event’ — WRONG: a recognised complication is not on the sentinel list. The tempting distractor pairs a genuinely severe-but-expected complication with the ‘sentinel’ label; only listed, wholly-preventable events qualify.",
   "viva": "Examiner probe: ‘Name three surgical sentinel events and how the WHO checklist prevents them.’ Wrong-site/patient/procedure + retained object; prevented by sign-in/time-out/sign-out, site marking, swab/instrument counts. Discriminator: candidate separates ‘sentinel/never event’ from ‘recognised complication’.",
   "mnemonic": "Surgical sentinel core = ‘4 W’s + ABO’: Wrong site, Wrong patient, Wrong procedure, retained Widget (foreign object), ABO-incompatible transfusion.",
