   "topic": "Incident reporting & Severity Assessment Code (SAC 1–4) — thresholds, timeframes & RCA trigger",
   "subarea": "Open disclosure & M&M",
   "trap": "Clinical incidents are risk-rated by SAC, where SAC 1 is the MOST severe (serious harm or death — or a near-miss that could have caused it — attributable to healthcare, not the underlying illness). The gotcha numbers: SAC 1 must be notified IMMEDIATELY internally and the health department/relevant authority within ~24–48h (jurisdiction-dependent), and it mandates a formal investigation (RCA or equivalent) — in WA the completed investigation report is due within 45 working days; in NSW SAC 1 is notified within 24h. SAC 1 events also trigger formal open disclosure. The scale runs 1 = worst (many jurisdictions use SAC 1–3; some 1–4), which catches students who assume a higher number = worse.",
   "source": "WA Health Clinical Incident Management Policy / SAC matrix (current); NSW CEC incident management (SAC 1 → notify within 24h → RCA/serious-incident review); ACSQHC incident-management guidance",
   "discriminator": "SAC 1 = serious harm/death or near-miss with that potential → immediate notification + formal investigation (RCA) + formal open disclosure. SAC 2 = moderate harm. SAC 3 = minimal/no harm → local review. Sentinel event = a defined wholly-preventable subset, always SAC 1, externally reportable. Don’t confuse ‘SAC 1’ (severity rank) with ‘sentinel event’ (specific national list) — all sentinel events are SAC 1, but not all SAC 1s are sentinel events.",
   "whatFirst": "Recognise/respond to harm → make patient safe → lodge incident report (e.g. ims+/Datix) → assign SAC → if SAC 1: notify line manager + clinical governance immediately, escalate to department/authority within the mandated time, commence open disclosure, initiate RCA/serious incident review. Quarantine/secure any device or retained item as evidence.",
   "redFlags": "Immediate escalation: death, serious/permanent harm, sentinel event, or a near-miss that could have killed/seriously harmed — these are SAC 1 and time-critical. Also escalate any actual or suspected sentinel event for external mandatory reporting.",
   "mcqTrap": "‘SAC 4 is the most serious incident requiring an RCA’ — WRONG: SAC 1 is the most serious (the scale is inverted; many jurisdictions use only SAC 1–3). Also wrong: ‘a near-miss with no actual harm doesn’t need reporting’ — a near-miss with serious-harm potential is SAC 1.",
   "viva": "Examiner probe (ISBAR): escalate a SAC 1. ‘I’dentify self/patient, ‘S’ituation (serious harm event), ‘B’ackground, ‘A’ssessment (this is a SAC 1 clinical incident), ‘R’ecommendation (immediate notification, open disclosure started, requesting RCA). Discriminator: candidate knows SAC 1 = highest severity + RCA + open disclosure.",
   "mnemonic": "‘SAC 1 = number 1 priority’ (lowest number = highest severity); SAC 1 → the 3 R’s: Report immediately, RCA, Reveal (open disclosure).",
