   "topic": "Levels & timing of open disclosure (clinician-led vs formal/higher-level)",
   "subarea": "Open disclosure & M&M",
   "trap": "Two tiers: (1) Clinician (lower-level) disclosure — the routine, informal bedside conversation by the treating team, begun generally WITHIN 24 HOURS of recognising harm; (2) Formal (higher-level) open disclosure — a structured, multidisciplinary, documented process led by a senior/trained clinician for serious harm, death, or where the patient/family wants it. The gotcha: open disclosure applies to ALL harm AND near-misses, not just severe events, and it is a process/ongoing dialogue — not a single one-off meeting.",
   "source": "Australian Open Disclosure Framework, ACSQHC (Feb 2014; current); NSQHS Standards (2nd ed) Clinical Governance Standard — open disclosure action; CEC (NSW) Open Disclosure process",
   "discriminator": "Clinician-level = treating team, soon (≈24h), routine harm. Formal/higher-level = trained lead + senior clinician + governance involvement, triggered by serious harm/death, permanent injury, patient request, or anticipated complaint. Open disclosure (clinical, patient-facing, transparency) is distinct from incident reporting (administrative, to the organisation) and M&M (clinician learning) — all three run in parallel.",
   "whatFirst": "Recognise harm → stabilise patient → clinician disclosure ASAP (≈24h) → lodge incident report → if serious/SAC 1, escalate to formal open disclosure + notify clinical governance. Maintain ongoing communication; provide updates and a follow-up after the investigation.",
   "redFlags": "Escalate to formal open disclosure: death, serious/permanent harm, sentinel/SAC 1 event, multiple patients affected, patient/family requests formal process, complaint or coronial/legal involvement likely.",
   "mcqTrap": "‘Open disclosure is a single meeting held after the root cause analysis is complete’ — WRONG: it is an ongoing process that begins within ~24h, before the investigation finishes. Also tempting-but-wrong: ‘only required for serious harm’ — it applies to all harm and near-misses.",
   "viva": "Examiner probe: ‘Who leads open disclosure and when?’ Treating clinician starts within ~24h; serious events get a trained, senior-led formal process with governance support. Discriminator: candidate separates the patient-facing disclosure from the internal incident report and the M&M.",
